# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: genomics-biology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] A **chromosome** is a package of DNA containing part or all of the genetic material of an organism.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In most chromosomes, the very long thin DNA fibers are coated with nucleosome-forming packaging proteins; in eukaryotic cells, the most important of these proteins are the histones.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Aided by chaperone proteins, the histones bind to and condense the DNA molecule to maintain its integrity.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] These eukaryotic chromosomes display a complex three-dimensional structure that has a significant role in transcriptional regulation.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Normally, chromosomes are visible under a light microscope only during the metaphase of cell division, where all chromosomes are aligned in the center of the cell in their condensed form.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] During metaphase, the duplicated structure (called a 'metaphase chromosome') is highly condensed and thus easiest to distinguish and study.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In animal cells, chromosomes reach their highest compaction level in anaphase during chromosome segregation.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Chromosomal recombination during meiosis and subsequent sexual reproduction plays a crucial role in genetic diversity.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] If these structures are manipulated incorrectly, through processes known as chromosomal instability and translocation, the cell may undergo mitotic catastrophe.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] This will usually cause the cell to initiate apoptosis, leading to its own death, but the process is occasionally hampered by cell mutations that result in the progression of cancer.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The term 'chromosome' is sometimes used in a wider sense to refer to the individualized portions of chromatin in cells, which may or may not be visible under light microscopy.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In a narrower sense, 'chromosome' can be used to refer to the individualized portions of chromatin during cell division, which are visible under light microscopy due to high condensation.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The word *chromosome* (/ˈkroʊməˌsoʊm, -ˌzoʊm/) comes from the Ancient Greek words χρῶμα (**khrôma**, "colour") and σῶμα (**sôma**, "body"), describing the strong staining produced by particular dyes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The term was coined by the German anatomist Heinrich Wilhelm Waldeyer, referring to the term 'chromatin', which was introduced by Walther Flemming.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Some of the early karyological terms have become outdated.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] For example, 'chromatin' (Flemming 1880) and 'chromosom' (Waldeyer 1888) both ascribe color to a non-colored state.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] (right) independently developed the chromosome theory of inheritance in 1902.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Otto Bütschli was the first scientist to recognize the structures now known as chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In a series of experiments beginning in the mid-1880s, Theodor Boveri gave definitive contributions to elucidating that chromosomes are the vectors of heredity, with two notions that became known as 'chromosome continuity' and 'chromosome individuality'.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Wilhelm Roux suggested that every chromosome carries a different genetic configuration, and Boveri was able to test and confirm this hypothesis.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Aided by the rediscovery at the start of the 1900s of Gregor Mendel's earlier experimental work, Boveri identified the connection between the rules of inheritance and the behaviour of the chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Two generations of American cytologists were influenced by Boveri: Edmund Beecher Wilson, Nettie Stevens, Walter Sutton and Theophilus Painter (Wilson, Stevens, and Painter actually worked with him).
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In his famous textbook, *The Cell in Development and Heredity*, Wilson linked together the independent work of Boveri and Sutton (both around 1902) by naming the chromosome theory of inheritance the 'Boveri–Sutton chromosome theory' (sometimes known as the 'Sutton–Boveri chromosome theory').
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Ernst Mayr remarks that the theory was hotly contested by some famous geneticists, including William Bateson, Wilhelm Johannsen, Richard Goldschmidt and T.H.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Morgan, all of a rather dogmatic mindset.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Eventually, absolute proof came from chromosome maps in Morgan's own laboratory.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The number of human chromosomes was published by Painter in 1923.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] By inspection through a microscope, he counted 24 pairs of chromosomes, giving 48 in total.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] His error was copied by others, and it was not until 1956 that the true number (46) was determined by Indonesian-born cytogeneticist Joe Hin Tjio.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The prokaryotes – bacteria and archaea – typically have a single circular chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The chromosomes of most bacteria (also called genophores), can range in size from only 130,000 base pairs in the endosymbiotic bacteria *Candidatus Hodgkinia cicadicola* and *Candidatus Tremblaya princeps*, to more than 14,000,000 base pairs in the soil-dwelling bacterium *Sorangium cellulosum*.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Some bacteria have more than one chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] For instance, Spirochaetes such as *Borrelia burgdorferi* (causing Lyme disease), contain a single *linear* chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] *Vibrios* typically carry two chromosomes of very different size.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Genomes of the genus *Burkholderia* carry one, two, or three chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Prokaryotic chromosomes have less sequence-based structure than eukaryotes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Bacteria typically have a one-point (the origin of replication) from which replication starts, whereas some archaea contain multiple replication origins.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The genes in prokaryotes are often organized in operons and do not usually contain introns, unlike eukaryotes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Instead, their DNA is organized into a structure called the nucleoid.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The nucleoid is a distinct structure and occupies a defined region of the bacterial cell.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] This structure is, however, dynamic and is maintained and remodeled by the actions of a range of histone-like proteins, which associate with the bacterial chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In archaea, the DNA in chromosomes is even more organized, with the DNA packaged within structures similar to eukaryotic nucleosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Certain bacteria also contain plasmids or other extrachromosomal DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] These are circular structures in the cytoplasm that contain cellular DNA and play a role in horizontal gene transfer.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In prokaryotes and viruses, the DNA is often densely packed and organized; in the case of archaea, by homology to eukaryotic histones, and in the case of bacteria, by histone-like proteins.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Bacterial chromosomes tend to be tethered to the plasma membrane of the bacteria.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In molecular biology application, this allows for its isolation from plasmid DNA by centrifugation of lysed bacteria and pelleting of the membranes (and the attached DNA).
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Prokaryotic chromosomes and plasmids are, like eukaryotic DNA, generally supercoiled.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The DNA must first be released into its relaxed state for access for transcription, regulation, and replication.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Each eukaryotic chromosome consists of a long linear DNA molecule associated with proteins, forming a compact complex of proteins and DNA called *chromatin.* Chromatin contains the vast majority of the DNA in an organism, but a small amount inherited maternally can be found in the mitochondria.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] It is present in most cells, with a few exceptions, for example, red blood cells.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Histones are responsible for the first and most basic unit of chromosome organization, the nucleosome.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Eukaryotes (cells with nuclei such as those found in plants, fungi, and animals) possess multiple large linear chromosomes contained in the cell's nucleus.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Each chromosome has one centromere, with one or two arms projecting from the centromere, although, under most circumstances, these arms are not visible as such.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In addition, most eukaryotes have a small circular mitochondrial genome, and some eukaryotes may have additional small circular or linear cytoplasmic chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In the nuclear chromosomes of eukaryotes, the uncondensed DNA exists in a semi-ordered structure, where it is wrapped around histones (structural proteins), forming a composite material called chromatin.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The packaging of DNA into nucleosomes causes a 10 nanometer fibre which may further condense up to 30 nm fibres.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Most of the euchromatin in interphase nuclei appears to be in the form of 30-nm fibers.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Chromatin structure is the more decondensed state, i.e. the 10-nm conformation allows transcription.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In the early stages of mitosis or meiosis (cell division), the chromatin double helix becomes more and more condensed.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] They cease to function as accessible genetic material (transcription stops) and become a compact transportable form.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The loops of thirty-nanometer chromatin fibers are thought to fold upon themselves further to form the compact metaphase chromosomes of mitotic cells.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The DNA is thus condensed about ten-thousand-fold.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The chromosome scaffold, which is made of proteins such as condensin, TOP2A and KIF4, plays an important role in holding the chromatin into compact chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Loops of thirty-nanometer structure further condense with scaffold into higher order structures.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] This highly compact form makes the individual chromosomes visible, and they form the classic four-arm structure, a pair of sister chromatids attached to each other at the centromere.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The shorter arms are called *p arms* (from the French *petit*, small) and the longer arms are called *q arms* (*q* follows *p* in the Latin alphabet; q-g "grande"; alternatively it is sometimes said q is short for *queue* meaning tail in French).
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] This is the only natural context in which individual chromosomes are visible with an optical microscope.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Mitotic metaphase chromosomes are best described by a linearly organized longitudinally compressed array of consecutive chromatin loops.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] During mitosis, microtubules grow from centrosomes located at opposite ends of the cell and also attach to the centromere at specialized structures called kinetochores, one of which is present on each sister chromatid.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] A special DNA base sequence in the region of the kinetochores provides, along with special proteins, longer-lasting attachment in this region.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The microtubules then pull the chromatids apart toward the centrosomes, so that each daughter cell inherits one set of chromatids.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Once the cells have divided, the chromatids are uncoiled and DNA can again be transcribed.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In spite of their appearance, chromosomes are structurally highly condensed, which enables these giant DNA structures to be contained within a cell nucleus.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Chromosomes in humans can be divided into two types: autosomes (body chromosome(s)) and allosome (sex chromosome(s)).
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Certain genetic traits are linked to a person's sex and are passed on through the sex chromosomes, which also contain other genetic hereditary information, in the case of Y chromosomes very little and in the case of X chromosomes a significant amount.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The autosomes contain the rest of the genetic hereditary information.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] All act in the same way during cell division.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Human cells have 23 pairs of chromosomes (22 pairs of autosomes and one pair of sex chromosomes), giving a total of 46 per cell.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In addition to these, human cells have many hundreds of copies of the mitochondrial genome.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Sequencing of the human genome has provided a great deal of information about each of the chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Below is a table compiling statistics for the chromosomes, based on the Sanger Institute's human genome information in the Vertebrate Genome Annotation (VEGA) database.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Number of genes is an estimate, as it is in part based on gene predictions.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Total chromosome length is an estimate as well, based on the estimated size of unsequenced heterochromatin regions.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In general, the karyotype is the characteristic chromosome complement of a eukaryote species.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The preparation and study of karyotypes is part of cytogenetics.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Although the replication and transcription of DNA is highly standardized in eukaryotes, the same cannot be said for their karyotypes, which are often highly variable.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] There may be variation between species in chromosome number and in detailed organization.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In some cases, there is significant variation within species.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Also, variation in karyotype may occur during development from the fertilized egg.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The technique of determining the karyotype is usually called *karyotyping*.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Cells can be locked part-way through division (in metaphase) in vitro (in a reaction vial) with colchicine.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] These cells are then stained, photographed, and arranged into a *karyogram*, with the set of chromosomes arranged, autosomes in order of length, and sex chromosomes (here X/Y) at the end.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Like many sexually reproducing species, humans have special gonosomes (sex chromosomes, in contrast to autosomes).
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] These are XX in females and XY in males.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Investigation into the human karyotype took many years to settle the most basic question: *How many chromosomes does a normal diploid human cell contain?* In 1912, Hans von Winiwarter reported 47 chromosomes in spermatogonia and 48 in oogonia, concluding an XX/XO sex determination mechanism.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In 1922, Painter was not certain whether the diploid number of man is 46 or 48, at first favouring 46.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] He revised his opinion later from 46 to 48, and he correctly insisted on humans having an XX/XY system.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Cutting up a photomicrograph and arranging the result into an indisputable karyogram.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] It took until 1954 before the human diploid number was confirmed as 46.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Considering the techniques of Winiwarter and Painter, their results were quite remarkable.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Chimpanzees, the closest living relatives to modern humans, have 48 chromosomes as do the other great apes: in humans two chromosomes fused to form chromosome 2.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Chromosomal aberrations are disruptions in the normal chromosomal content of a cell.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] They can cause genetic conditions in humans, such as Down syndrome, although most aberrations have little to no effect.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Some chromosome abnormalities do not cause disease in carriers, such as translocations, or chromosomal inversions, although they may lead to a higher chance of bearing a child with a chromosome disorder.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Abnormal numbers of chromosomes or chromosome sets, called aneuploidy, may be lethal or may give rise to genetic disorders.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Genetic counseling is offered for families that may carry a chromosome rearrangement.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The gain or loss of DNA from chromosomes can lead to a variety of genetic disorders.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Exposure of males to certain lifestyle, environmental and/or occupational hazards may increase the risk of aneuploid spermatozoa.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] In particular, risk of aneuploidy is increased by tobacco smoking, and occupational exposure to benzene, insecticides, and perfluorinated compounds.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Increased aneuploidy is often associated with increased DNA damage in spermatozoa.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The number of chromosomes in eukaryotes is highly variable.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] It is possible for chromosomes to fuse or break and thus evolve into novel karyotypes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Chromosomes can also be fused artificially.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] For example, when the 16 chromosomes of yeast were fused into one giant chromosome, it was found that the cells were still viable with only somewhat reduced growth rates.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The tables below give the total number of chromosomes (including sex chromosomes) in a cell nucleus for various eukaryotes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Most are diploid, such as humans who have 22 different types of autosomes—each present as two homologous pairs—and two sex chromosomes, giving 46 chromosomes in total.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Some other organisms have more than two copies of their chromosome types, for example bread wheat which is *hexaploid*, having six copies of seven different chromosome types for a total of 42 chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Normal members of a particular eukaryotic species all have the same number of nuclear chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Other eukaryotic chromosomes, i.e., mitochondrial and plasmid-like small chromosomes, are much more variable in number, and there may be thousands of copies per cell.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Asexually reproducing species have one set of chromosomes that are the same in all body cells.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] However, asexual species can be either haploid or diploid.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Sexually reproducing species have somatic cells (body cells) that are diploid [2n], having two sets of chromosomes (23 pairs in humans), one set from the mother and one from the father.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Gametes (reproductive cells) are haploid [n], having one set of chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Gametes are produced by meiosis of a diploid germline cell, during which the matching chromosomes of father and mother can exchange small parts of themselves (crossover) and thus create new chromosomes that are not inherited solely from either parent.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] When a male and a female gamete merge during fertilization, a new diploid organism is formed.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Some animal and plant species are polyploid [Xn], having more than two sets of homologous chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Important crops such as tobacco or wheat are often polyploid, compared to their ancestral species.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Wheat has a haploid number of seven chromosomes, still seen in some cultivars as well as the wild progenitors.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The more common types of pasta and bread wheat are polyploid, having 28 (tetraploid) and 42 (hexaploid) chromosomes, compared to the 14 (diploid) chromosomes in wild wheat.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Prokaryote species generally have one copy of each major chromosome, but most cells can easily survive with multiple copies.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] For example, *Buchnera*, a symbiont of aphids, has multiple copies of its chromosome, ranging from 10 to 400 copies per cell.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] However, in some large bacteria, such as *Epulopiscium fishelsoni* up to 100,000 copies of the chromosome can be present.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] Plasmids and plasmid-like small chromosomes are, as in eukaryotes, highly variable in copy number.
[src:genomics-biology/chromosome] The number of plasmids in the cell is almost entirely determined by the rate of division of the plasmid – fast division causes high copy number.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] The comparative genomic analysis begins with a simple comparison of the general features of genomes such as genome size, number of genes, and chromosome number.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Table 1 presents data on several fully sequenced model organisms, and highlights some striking findings.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] For instance, while the tiny flowering plant *Arabidopsis thaliana* has a smaller genome than that of the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* (157 million base pairs v.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] 165 million base pairs, respectively) it possesses nearly twice as many genes (25,000 v.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In fact, *A. thaliana* has approximately the same number of genes as humans (25,000).
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Thus, a very early lesson learned in the **genomic era** is that genome size does not correlate with evolutionary status, nor is the number of genes proportionate to genome size.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In comparative genomics, synteny is the preserved order of genes on chromosomes of related species indicating their descent from a common ancestor.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Synteny provides a framework in which the conservation of homologous genes and gene order is identified between genomes of different species.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Synteny blocks are more formally defined as regions of chromosomes between genomes that share a common order of homologous genes derived from a common ancestor.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Alternative names such as conserved synteny or collinearity have been used interchangeably.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Furthermore, comparing two genomes not only reveals conserved domains or synteny but also aids in detecting copy number variations, single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs), indels, and other genomic structural variations.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Virtually started as soon as the whole genomes of two organisms became available (that is, the genomes of the bacteria *Haemophilus influenzae* and *Mycoplasma genitalium*) in 1995, comparative genomics is now a standard component of the analysis of every new genome sequence.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] With the explosion in the number of genome projects due to the advancements in DNA sequencing technologies, particularly the next-generation sequencing methods in late 2000s, this field has become more sophisticated, making it possible to deal with many genomes in a single study.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative genomics has revealed high levels of similarity between closely related organisms, such as humans and chimpanzees, and, more surprisingly, similarity between seemingly distantly related organisms, such as humans and the yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] It has also showed the extreme diversity of the gene composition in different evolutionary lineages.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative genomics has a root in the comparison of virus genomes in the early 1980s.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] For example, small RNA viruses infecting animals (picornaviruses) and those infecting plants (cowpea mosaic virus) were compared and turned out to share significant sequence similarity and, in part, the order of their genes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In 1986, the first comparative genomic study at a larger scale was published, comparing the genomes of varicella-zoster virus and Epstein-Barr virus that contained more than 100 genes each.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] The first complete genome sequence of a cellular organism, that of *Haemophilus influenzae* Rd, was published in 1995.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] The second genome sequencing paper was of the small parasitic bacterium *Mycoplasma genitalium* published in the same year.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Starting from this paper, reports on new genomes inevitably became comparative-genomic studies.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] With the publication of the large genomes of vertebrates in the 2000s, including human, the Japanese pufferfish *Takifugu rubripes*, and mouse, precomputed results of large genome comparisons have been released for downloading or for visualization in a genome browser.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Instead of undertaking their own analyses, most biologists can access these large cross-species comparisons and avoid the impracticality caused by the size of the genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Next-generation sequencing methods, which were first introduced in 2007, have produced an enormous amount of genomic data and have allowed researchers to generate multiple (prokaryotic) draft genome sequences at once.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] These methods can also quickly uncover single-nucleotide polymorphisms, insertions and deletions by mapping unassembled reads against a well annotated reference genome, and thus provide a list of possible gene differences that may be the basis for any functional variation among strains.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] One character of biology is evolution, evolutionary theory is also the theoretical foundation of comparative genomics, and at the same time the results of comparative genomics unprecedentedly enriched and developed the theory of evolution.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] When two or more of the genome sequence are compared, one can deduce the evolutionary relationships of the sequences in a phylogenetic tree.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Based on a variety of biological genome data and the study of vertical and horizontal evolution processes, one can understand vital parts of the gene structure and its regulatory function.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Similarity of related genomes is the basis of comparative genomics.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] If two creatures have a recent common ancestor, the differences between the two species genomes are evolved from the ancestors' genome.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] The closer the relationship between two organisms, the higher the similarities between their genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] If there is close relationship between them, then their genome will display a linear behaviour (synteny), namely some or all of the genetic sequences are conserved.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Thus, the genome sequences can be used to identify gene function, by analyzing their homology (sequence similarity) to genes of known function.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Orthologous sequences are related sequences in different species: a gene exists in the original species, the species divided into two species, so genes in new species are orthologous to the sequence in the original species.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Paralogous sequences are separated by gene cloning (gene duplication): if a particular gene in the genome is copied, then the copy of the two sequences is paralogous to the original gene.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] A pair of orthologous sequences is called orthologous pairs (orthologs), a pair of paralogous sequence is called collateral pairs (paralogs).
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Orthologous pairs usually have the same or similar function, which is not necessarily the case for collateral pairs.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In collateral pairs, the sequences tend to evolve into having different functions.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative genomics exploits both similarities and differences in the proteins, RNA, and regulatory regions of different organisms to infer how selection has acted upon these elements.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Those elements that are responsible for similarities between different species should be conserved through time (stabilizing selection), while those elements responsible for differences among species should be divergent (positive selection).
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Finally, those elements that are unimportant to the evolutionary success of the organism will be unconserved (selection is neutral).
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] One of the important goals of the field is the identification of the mechanisms of eukaryotic genome evolution.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] It is however often complicated by the multiplicity of events that have taken place throughout the history of individual lineages, leaving only distorted and superimposed traces in the genome of each living organism.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] For this reason comparative genomics studies of small model organisms (for example the model Caenorhabditis elegans and closely related Caenorhabditis briggsae) are of great importance to advance our understanding of general mechanisms of evolution.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative genomics plays a crucial role in identifying copy number variations (CNVs) and understanding their significance in evolution.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] CNVs, which involve deletions or duplications of large segments of DNA, are recognized as a major source of genetic diversity, influencing gene structure, dosage, and regulation.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] While single nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) are more common, CNVs impact larger genomic regions and can have profound effects on phenotype and diversity.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Recent studies suggest that CNVs constitute around 4.8–9.5% of the human genome and have a substantial functional and evolutionary impact.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In mammals, CNVs contribute significantly to population diversity, influencing gene expression and various phenotypic traits.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative genomics analyses of human and chimpanzee genomes have revealed that CNVs may play a greater role in evolutionary change compared to single nucleotide changes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Research indicates that CNVs affect more nucleotides than individual base-pair changes, with about 2.7% of the genome affected by CNVs compared to 1.2% by SNPs.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Moreover, while many CNVs are shared between humans and chimpanzees, a significant portion is unique to each species.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Additionally, CNVs have been associated with genetic diseases in humans, highlighting their importance in human health.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Despite this, many questions about CNVs remain unanswered, including their origin and contributions to evolutionary adaptation and disease.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Ongoing research aims to address these questions using techniques like comparative genomic hybridization, which allows for a detailed examination of CNVs and their significance.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] When investigators examined the raw sequence data of the human and chimpanzee.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative genomics holds profound significance across various fields, including medical research, basic biology, and biodiversity conservation.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] To tackle this challenge, comparative genomics offers a solution by pinpointing nucleotide positions that have remained unchanged over millions of years of evolution.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] These conserved regions indicate potential sites where genetic alterations could have detrimental effects on an organism's fitness, thus guiding the search for disease-causing variants.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Moreover, comparative genomics holds promise in unraveling the mechanisms of gene evolution, environmental adaptations, gender-specific differences, and population variations across vertebrate lineages.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Furthermore, comparative studies enable the identification of genomic signatures of selection—regions in the genome that have undergone preferential increase and fixation in populations due to their functional significance in specific processes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] For instance, in animal genetics, indigenous cattle exhibit superior disease resistance and environmental adaptability but lower productivity compared to exotic breeds.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Through comparative genomic analyses, significant genomic signatures responsible for these unique traits can be identified.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Using insights from this signature, breeders can make informed decisions to enhance breeding strategies and promote breed development.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] ==Methods==Computational approaches are necessary for genome comparisons, given the large amount of data encoded in genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Many tools are now publicly available, ranging from whole genome comparisons to gene expression analysis.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] This includes approaches from systems and control, information theory, string analysis and data mining.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Computational approaches will remain critical for research and teaching, especially when information science and genome biology is taught in conjunction.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Pangenome analysis is another comparative-genomics method: in presence-absence pangenomes, genes are divided into a core genome shared by all sampled members of a population and an accessory genome present in only some members.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In microbial comparative genomics, comparative pangenomics can use this core-versus-accessory structure to relate gene-content variation to clinically relevant traits such as virulence and antimicrobial resistance.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative genomics starts with basic comparisons of genome size and gene density.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] For instance, genome size is important for coding capacity and possibly for regulatory reasons.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] High gene density facilitates genome annotation, analysis of environmental selection.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] By contrast, low gene density hampers the mapping of genetic disease as in the human genome.=== Sequence alignment === Alignments are used to capture information about similar sequences such as ancestry, common evolutionary descent, or common structure and function.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Alignments can be done for both nucleotide and protein sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Alignments consist of local or global pairwise alignments, and multiple sequence alignments.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] One way to find global alignments is to use a dynamic programming algorithm known as Needleman-Wunsch algorithm whereas Smith–Waterman algorithm used to find local alignments.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] With the exponential growth of sequence databases and the emergence of longer sequences, there's a heightened interest in faster, approximate, or heuristic alignment procedures.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Among these, the **FASTA** and **BLAST** algorithms are prominent for local pairwise alignment.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Recent years have witnessed the development of programs tailored to aligning lengthy sequences, such as **MUMmer** (1999), **BLASTZ** (2003), and **AVID** (2003).
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] While BLASTZ adopts a local approach, MUMmer and AVID are geared towards global alignment.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] To harness the benefits of both local and global alignment approaches, one effective strategy involves integrating them.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Initially, a rapid variant of BLAST known as **BLAT** is employed to identify homologous "anchor" regions.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] These anchors are subsequently scrutinized to identify sets exhibiting conserved order and orientation.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Such sets of anchors are then subjected to alignment using a global strategy.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Additionally, ongoing efforts focus on optimizing existing algorithms to handle the vast amount of genome sequence data by enhancing their speed.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Furthermore, **MAVID** stands out as another noteworthy pairwise alignment program specifically designed for aligning multiple genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Whole-genome alignment (WGA) involves predicting evolutionary relationships at the nucleotide level between two or more genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] It integrates elements of colinear sequence alignment and gene orthology prediction, presenting a greater challenge due to the vast size and intricate nature of whole genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Despite its complexity, numerous methods have emerged to tackle this problem because WGAs play a crucial role in various genome-wide analyses, such as phylogenetic inference, genome annotation, and function prediction.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Thereby, SyRI (Synteny and Rearrangement Identifier) is one such method that utilizes whole genome alignment and it is designed to identify both structural and sequence differences between two whole-genome assemblies.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] By taking WGAs as input, SyRI initially scans for disparities in genome structures.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Subsequently, it identifies local sequence variations within both rearranged and non-rearranged (syntenic) regions.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Another computational method for comparative genomics is phylogenetic reconstruction.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] It is used to describe evolutionary relationships in terms of common ancestors.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] The relationships are usually represented in a tree called a phylogenetic tree.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Similarly, coalescent theory is a retrospective model to trace alleles of a gene in a population to a single ancestral copy shared by members of the population.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] This is also known as the most recent common ancestor.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Analysis based on coalescence theory tries predicting the amount of time between the introduction of a mutation and a particular allele or gene distribution in a population.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] This time period is equal to how long ago the most recent common ancestor existed.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] The inheritance relationships are visualized in a form similar to a phylogenetic tree.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Coalescence (or the gene genealogy) can be visualized using dendrograms.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] An additional method in comparative genomics is genetic mapping.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In genetic mapping, visualizing synteny is one way to see the preserved order of genes on chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] It is usually used for chromosomes of related species, both of which result from a common ancestor.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] This and other methods can shed light on evolutionary history.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] A recent study used comparative genomics to reconstruct 16 ancestral karyotypes across the mammalian phylogeny.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] The computational reconstruction showed how chromosomes rearranged themselves during mammal evolution.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] It gave insight into conservation of select regions often associated with the control of developmental processes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In addition, it helped to provide an understanding of chromosome evolution and genetic diseases associated with DNA rearrangements.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Computational tools for analyzing sequences and complete genomes are developing quickly due to the availability of large amount of genomic data.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] At the same time, comparative analysis tools are progressed and improved.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In the challenges about these analyses, it is very important to visualize the comparative results.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Visualization of sequence conservation is a tough task of comparative sequence analysis.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] As we know, it is highly inefficient to examine the alignment of long genomic regions manually.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Internet-based genome browsers provide many useful tools for investigating genomic sequences due to integrating all sequence-based biological information on genomic regions.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] When we extract large amount of relevant biological data, they can be very easy to use and less time-consuming.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] An advantage of using online tools is that these websites are being developed and updated constantly.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] There are many new settings and content can be used online to improve efficiency.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Agriculture is a field that reaps the benefits of comparative genomics.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Identifying the loci of advantageous genes is a key step in breeding crops that are optimized for greater yield, cost-efficiency, quality, and disease resistance.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] For example, one genome wide association study conducted on 517 rice landraces revealed 80 loci associated with several categories of agronomic performance, such as grain weight, amylose content, and drought tolerance.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Many of the loci were previously uncharacterized.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Not only is this methodology powerful, it is also quick.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Previous methods of identifying loci associated with agronomic performance required several generations of carefully monitored breeding of parent strains, a time-consuming effort that is unnecessary for comparative genomic studies.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] The medical field also benefits from the study of comparative genomics.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In an approach known as reverse vaccinology, researchers can discover candidate antigens for vaccine development by analyzing the genome of a pathogen or a family of pathogens.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Applying a comparative genomics approach by analyzing the genomes of several related pathogens can lead to the development of vaccines that are multi-protective.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] A team of researchers employed such an approach to create a universal vaccine for Group B Streptococcus, a group of bacteria responsible for severe neonatal infection.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative genomics can also be used to generate specificity for vaccines against pathogens that are closely related to commensal microorganisms.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] For example, researchers used comparative genomic analysis of commensal and pathogenic strains of *E. coli* to identify pathogen-specific genes as a basis for finding antigens that result in immune response against pathogenic strains but not commensal ones.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In May 2019, using the Global Genome Set, a team in the UK and Australia sequenced thousands of globally collected isolates of Group A Streptococcus, providing potential targets for developing a vaccine against the pathogen, also known as *S. pyogenes*.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Personalized Medicine, enabled by Comparative Genomics, represents a revolutionary approach in healthcare, tailoring medical treatment and disease prevention to the individual patient's genetic makeup.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] By analyzing genetic variations across populations and comparing them with an individual's genome, clinicians can identify specific genetic markers associated with disease susceptibility, drug metabolism, and treatment response.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] By identifying genetic variants associated with drug metabolism pathways, drug targets, and adverse reactions, personalized medicine can optimize medication selection, dosage, and treatment regimens for individual patients.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] This approach minimizes the risk of adverse drug reactions, enhances treatment efficacy, and improves patient outcomes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Cancer Genomics represents a cutting-edge field within oncology that leverages comparative genomics to revolutionize cancer diagnosis, treatment, and prevention strategies.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative genomics plays a crucial role in cancer research by identifying driver mutations, and providing comprehensive analyses of mutations, copy number alterations, structural variants, gene expression, and DNA methylation profiles in large-scale studies across different cancer types.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] By analyzing the genomes of cancer cells and comparing them with healthy cells, researchers can uncover key genetic alterations driving tumorigenesis, tumor progression, and metastasis.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] This deep understanding of the genomic landscape of cancer has profound implications for precision oncology.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Moreover, Comparative Genomics is instrumental in elucidating mechanisms of drug resistance—a major challenge in cancer treatment.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] T cells (also known as a T lymphocytes or a thymocytes) are immune cells that grow from stem cells in the bone marrow.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] They assist to defend the body from infection and may aid in the fight against cancer.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Because of their morphological, physiological, and genetic resemblance to humans, mice and rats have long been the preferred species for biomedical research animal models.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative Medicine Research is built on the ability to use information from one species to understand the same processes in another.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] We can get new insights into molecular pathways by comparing human and mouse T cells and their effects on the immune system utilizing comparative genomics.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In order to comprehend its TCRs and their genes, Glusman conducted research on the sequencing of the human and mouse T cell receptor loci.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] TCR genes are well-known and serve as a significant resource for supporting functional genomics and understanding how genes and intergenic regions of the genome contribute to biological processes.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] T-cell immune receptors are important in seeing the world of pathogens in the cellular immune system.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] One of the reasons for sequencing the human and mouse TCR loci was to match the orthologous gene family sequences and discover conserved areas using comparative genomics.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] These, it was thought, would reflect two sorts of biological information: (1) exons and (2) regulatory sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] In fact, the majority of V, D, J, and C exons could be identified in this method.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Both human and mouse motifs are largely clustered in the 200 bp [Figure 2], the known 3′ enhancers in the TCR/ were identified, and a conserved region of 100 bp in the mouse J intron was subsequently shown to have a regulatory function.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparisons of the genomic sequences within each physical site or location of a specific gene on a chromosome (locs) and across species allow for research on other mechanisms and other regulatory signals.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Some suggest new hypotheses about the evolution of TCRs, to be tested (and improved) by comparison to the TCR gene complement of other vertebrate species.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] A comparative genomic investigation of humans and mice will obviously allow for the discovery and annotation of many other genes, as well as identifying in other species for regulatory sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative genomics also opens up new avenues in other areas of research.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] As DNA sequencing technology has become more accessible, the number of sequenced genomes has grown.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] With the increasing reservoir of available genomic data, the potency of comparative genomic inference has grown as well.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] A notable case of this increased potency is found in recent primate research.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative genomic methods have allowed researchers to gather information about genetic variation, differential gene expression, and evolutionary dynamics in primates that were indiscernible using previous data and methods.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Comparative genomics has also become increasingly important in microbial ecology and plant–microbe interaction research.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] By comparing large collections of bacterial genomes from different environments, researchers have been able to identify genes and functional pathways associated with adaptation to specific ecological niches, such as plant-associated versus free-living lifestyles.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] When combined with transcriptomic or metagenomic data, comparative genomic approaches can link gene conservation and abundance to ecological relevance, revealing bacterial genes that are consistently enriched and transcriptionally active in plant-associated environments.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] The **Great Ape Genome Project** used comparative genomic methods to investigate genetic variation with reference to the six great ape species, finding healthy levels of variation in their gene pool despite shrinking population size.
[src:genomics-biology/comparative-genomics] Another study showed that patterns of DNA methylation, which are a known regulation mechanism for gene expression, differ in the prefrontal cortex of humans versus chimps, and implicated this difference in the evolutionary divergence of the two species.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] The Human Genome Project is a well known example of a genome project.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Genome assembly refers to the process of taking a large number of short DNA sequences and reassembling them to create a representation of the original chromosomes from which the DNA originated.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] In a shotgun sequencing project, all the DNA from a source (usually a single organism, anything from a bacterium to a mammal) is first fractured into millions of small pieces.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] These pieces are then "read" by automated sequencing machines.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] A genome assembly algorithm works by taking all the pieces and aligning them to one another, and detecting all places where two of the short sequences, or *reads*, overlap.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] These overlapping reads can be merged, and the process continues.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Genome assembly is a very difficult computational problem, made more difficult because many genomes contain large numbers of identical sequences, known as repeats.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] These repeats can be thousands of nucleotides long, and occur different locations, especially in the large genomes of plants and animals.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] The resulting (draft) genome sequence is produced by combining the information sequenced contigs and then employing linking information to create scaffolds.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Scaffolds are positioned along the physical map of the chromosomes creating a "golden path".
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Originally, most large-scale DNA sequencing centers developed their own software for assembling the sequences that they produced.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] However, this has changed as the software has grown more complex and as the number of sequencing centers has increased.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] An example of such assembler *Short Oligonucleotide Analysis Package* developed by BGI for de novo assembly of human-sized genomes, alignment, SNP detection, resequencing, indel finding, and structural variation analysis.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Since the 1980s, molecular biology and bioinformatics have created the need for DNA annotation.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] DNA annotation or genome annotation is the process of identifying attaching biological information to sequences, and particularly in identifying the locations of genes and determining what those genes do.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] When sequencing a genome, there are usually regions that are difficult to sequence (often regions with highly repetitive DNA).
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Thus, 'completed' genome sequences are rarely ever complete, and terms such as 'working draft' or 'essentially complete' have been used to more accurately describe the status of such genome projects.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Even when every base pair of a genome sequence has been determined, there are still likely to be errors present because DNA sequencing is not a completely accurate process.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] It could also be argued that a complete genome project should include the sequences of mitochondria and (for plants) chloroplasts as these organelles have their own genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] It is often reported that the goal of sequencing a genome is to obtain information about the complete set of genes in that particular genome sequence.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] The proportion of a genome that encodes for genes may be very small (particularly in eukaryotes such as humans, where coding DNA may only account for a few percent of the entire sequence).
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] However, it is not always possible (or desirable) to only sequence the coding regions separately.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Also, as scientists understand more about the role of this noncoding DNA (often referred to as junk DNA), it will become more important to have a complete genome sequence as a background to understanding the genetics and biology of any given organism.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] In many ways genome projects do not confine themselves to only determining a DNA sequence of an organism.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Such projects may also include gene prediction to find out where the genes are in a genome, and what those genes do.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] There may also be related projects to sequence ESTs or mRNAs to help find out where the genes actually are.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Historically, when sequencing eukaryotic genomes (such as the worm *Caenorhabditis elegans*) it was common to first map the genome to provide a series of landmarks across the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Rather than sequence a chromosome in one go, it would be sequenced piece by piece (with the prior knowledge of approximately where that piece is located on the larger chromosome).
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Changes in technology and in particular improvements to the processing power of computers, means that genomes can now be 'shotgun sequenced' in one go (there are caveats to this approach though when compared to the traditional approach).
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Improvements in DNA sequencing technology have meant that the cost of sequencing a new genome sequence has steadily fallen (in terms of cost per base pair) and newer technology has also meant that genomes can be sequenced far more quickly.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] Secondary emphasis is placed on species whose genomes will help answer important questions in molecular evolution (e.g. the common chimpanzee).
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] In the future, it is likely that it will become even cheaper and quicker to sequence a genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] This will allow for complete genome sequences to be determined from many different individuals of the same species.
[src:genomics-biology/genome-project] For humans, this will allow us to better understand aspects of human genetic diversity.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] A **genome** is all the genetic information of an organism or cell.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] It consists of nucleotide sequences of DNA (or RNA in RNA viruses).
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The nuclear genome includes protein-coding genes and non-coding genes, other functional regions of the genome such as regulatory sequences (see non-coding DNA), and often a substantial fraction of junk DNA with no evident function.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Almost all eukaryotes have mitochondria and a small mitochondrial genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Algae and plants also contain chloroplasts with a chloroplast genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The study of the genome is called genomics.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The genomes of many organisms have been sequenced and various regions have been annotated.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The first genome to be sequenced was that of the virus φX174 in 1977; the first genome sequence of a prokaryote (*Haemophilus influenzae*) was published in 1995; the yeast (*Saccharomyces cerevisiae*) genome was the first eukaryotic genome to be sequenced in 1996.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The Human Genome Project was started in October 1990, and the first draft sequences of the human genome were reported in February 2001.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The term *genome* was created in 1920 by Hans Winkler, professor of botany at the University of Hamburg, Germany.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The website Oxford Dictionaries and the Online Etymology Dictionary suggest the name is a blend of the words *gene* and *chromosome*.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] However, see omics for a more thorough discussion.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] A few related *-ome* words already existed, such as *biome* and *rhizome*, forming a vocabulary into which *genome* fits systematically.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] In the scientific literature, the term 'genome' usually refers to the large chromosomal DNA molecules in bacteria.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Eukaryotic genomes are even more difficult to define because almost all eukaryotic species contain nuclear chromosomes plus extra DNA molecules in the mitochondria.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] In addition, algae and plants have chloroplast DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Most textbooks make a distinction between the nuclear genome and the organelle (mitochondria and chloroplast) genomes so when they speak of, say, the human genome, they are only referring to the genetic material in the nucleus.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] This is the most common use of 'genome' in the scientific literature.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Most eukaryotes are diploid, meaning that there are two of each chromosome in the nucleus but the 'genome' refers to only one copy of each chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Some eukaryotes have distinctive sex chromosomes, such as the X and Y chromosomes of mammals, so the technical definition of the genome must include both copies of the sex chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] For example, the standard reference genome of humans consists of one copy of each of the 22 autosomes plus one X chromosome and one Y chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] A **genome sequence** is the complete list of the nucleotides (A, C, G, and T for DNA genomes) that make up all the chromosomes of an individual or a species.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Within a species, the vast majority of nucleotides are identical between individuals, but sequencing multiple individuals is necessary to understand the genetic diversity.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] In 1976, Walter Fiers at the University of Ghent (Belgium) was the first to establish the complete nucleotide sequence of a viral RNA-genome (Bacteriophage MS2).
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The next year, Fred Sanger completed the first DNA-genome sequence: Phage X174, of 5386 base pairs.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The first bacterial genome to be sequenced was that of Haemophilus influenzae, completed by a team at The Institute for Genomic Research in 1995.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] A few months later, the first eukaryotic genome was completed, with sequences of the 16 chromosomes of budding yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* published as the result of a European-led effort begun in the mid-1980s.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The first genome sequence for an archaeon, *Methanococcus jannaschii*, was completed in 1996, again by The Institute for Genomic Research.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The development of new technologies has made genome sequencing dramatically cheaper and easier, and the number of complete genome sequences is growing rapidly.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The US National Institutes of Health maintains one of several comprehensive databases of genomic information.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Among the thousands of completed genome sequencing projects include those for rice, a mouse, the plant *Arabidopsis thaliana*, the puffer fish, and the bacteria E. coli.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] In December 2013, scientists first sequenced the entire *genome* of a Neanderthal, an extinct species of humans.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The genome was extracted from the toe bone of a 130,000-year-old Neanderthal found in a Siberian cave.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Viral genomes can be composed of either RNA or DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The genomes of RNA viruses can be either single-stranded RNA or double-stranded RNA, and may contain one or more separate RNA molecules (segments: monopartit or multipartit genome).
[src:genomics-biology/genome] DNA viruses can have either single-stranded or double-stranded genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Most DNA virus genomes are composed of a single, linear molecule of DNA, but some are made up of a circular DNA molecule.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Prokaryotes and eukaryotes have DNA genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Archaea and most bacteria have a single circular chromosome, however, some bacterial species have linear or multiple chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Most prokaryotes have very little repetitive DNA in their genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] *Serratia symbiotica*) have reduced genomes and a high fraction of pseudogenes: only ~40% of their DNA encodes proteins.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Some bacteria have auxiliary genetic material, also part of their genome, which is carried in plasmids.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] For this, the word *genome* should not be used as a synonym of *chromosome*.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Eukaryotic genomes are composed of one or more linear DNA chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The number of chromosomes varies widely from Jack jumper ants and an asexual nemotode, which each have only one pair, to a fern species that has 720 pairs.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] It is surprising the amount of DNA that eukaryotic genomes contain compared to other genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The amount is even more than what is necessary for DNA protein-coding and noncoding genes because eukaryotic genomes show as much as 64,000-fold variation in their sizes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] However, this special characteristic is caused by the presence of repetitive DNA, and transposable elements (TEs).
[src:genomics-biology/genome] A typical human cell has two copies of each of 22 autosomes, one inherited from each parent, plus two sex chromosomes, making it diploid.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Gametes, such as ova, sperm, spores, and pollen, are haploid, meaning they carry only one copy of each chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] In addition to the chromosomes in the nucleus, organelles such as the chloroplasts and mitochondria have their own DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Mitochondria are sometimes said to have their own genome often referred to as the "mitochondrial genome".
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The DNA found within the chloroplast may be referred to as the "plastome".
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Like the bacteria they originated from, mitochondria and chloroplasts have a circular chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Unlike prokaryotes where exon-intron organization of protein coding genes exists but is rather exceptional, eukaryotes generally have these features in their genes and their genomes contain variable amounts of repetitive DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] In mammals and plants, the majority of the genome is composed of repetitive DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] High-throughput technology makes sequencing to assemble new genomes accessible to everyone.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Sequence polymorphisms are typically discovered by comparing resequenced isolates to a reference, whereas analyses of coverage depth and mapping topology can provide details regarding structural variations such as chromosomal translocations and segmental duplications.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] DNA sequences that carry the instructions to make proteins are referred to as coding sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The proportion of the genome occupied by coding sequences varies widely.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] A larger genome does not necessarily contain more genes, and the proportion of non-repetitive DNA decreases along with increasing genome size in complex eukaryotes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Noncoding sequences include introns, sequences for non-coding RNAs, regulatory regions, and repetitive DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Noncoding sequences make up 98% of the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] There are two categories of repetitive DNA in the genome: tandem repeats and interspersed repeats.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Short, non-coding sequences that are repeated head-to-tail are called tandem repeats.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Microsatellites consisting of 2–5 basepair repeats, while minisatellite repeats are 30–35 bp.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Tandem repeats make up about 4% of the human genome and 9% of the fruit fly genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] For example, telomeres are composed of the tandem repeat TTAGGG in mammals, and they play an important role in protecting the ends of the chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] In other cases, expansions in the number of tandem repeats in exons or introns can cause disease.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] For example, the human gene huntingtin (Htt) typically contains 6–29 tandem repeats of the nucleotides CAG (encoding a polyglutamine tract).
[src:genomics-biology/genome] An expansion to over 36 repeats results in Huntington's disease, a neurodegenerative disease.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Twenty human disorders are known to result from similar tandem repeat expansions in various genes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The mechanism by which proteins with expanded polygulatamine tracts cause death of neurons is not fully understood.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] One possibility is that the proteins fail to fold properly and avoid degradation, instead accumulating in aggregates that also sequester important transcription factors, thereby altering gene expression.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Tandem repeats are usually caused by slippage during replication, unequal crossing-over and gene conversion.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Transposable elements (TEs) are sequences of DNA with a defined structure that are able to change their location in the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] TEs are categorized as either as a mechanism that replicates by copy-and-paste or as a mechanism that can be excised from the genome and inserted at a new location.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] In the human genome, there are three important classes of TEs that make up more than 45% of the human DNA; these classes are The long interspersed nuclear elements (LINEs), The interspersed nuclear elements (SINEs), and endogenous retroviruses.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] These elements have a big potential to modify the genetic control in a host organism.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The movement of TEs is a driving force of genome evolution in eukaryotes because their insertion can disrupt gene functions, homologous recombination between TEs can produce duplications, and TE can shuffle exons and regulatory sequences to new locations.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Retrotransposons are found mostly in eukaryotes but not found in prokaryotes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Retrotransposons form a large portion of the genomes of many eukaryotes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] A retrotransposon is a transposable element that transposes through an RNA intermediate.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Retrotransposons are composed of DNA, but are transcribed into RNA for transposition, then the RNA transcript is copied back to DNA formation with the help of a specific enzyme called reverse transcriptase.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] A retrotransposon that carries reverse transcriptase in its sequence can trigger its own transposition but retrotransposons that lack a reverse transcriptase must use reverse transcriptase synthesized by another retrotransposon.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Retrotransposons can be transcribed into RNA, which are then duplicated at another site into the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Retrotransposons can be divided into long terminal repeats (LTRs) and non-long terminal repeats (Non-LTRs).
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Long interspersed elements (LINEs) encode genes for reverse transcriptase and endonuclease, making them autonomous transposable elements.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The human genome has around 500,000 LINEs, taking around 17% of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Short interspersed elements (SINEs) are usually less than 500 base pairs and are non-autonomous, so they rely on the proteins encoded by LINEs for transposition.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The Alu element is the most common SINE found in primates.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] It is about 350 base pairs and occupies about 11% of the human genome with around 1,500,000 copies.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] DNA transposons encode a transposase enzyme between inverted terminal repeats.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] When expressed, the transposase recognizes the terminal inverted repeats that flank the transposon and catalyzes its excision and reinsertion in a new site.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] This cut-and-paste mechanism typically reinserts transposons near their original location (within 100 kb).
[src:genomics-biology/genome] DNA transposons are found in bacteria and make up 3% of the human genome and 12% of the genome of the roundworm *C. elegans*.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Genome size is the total number of the DNA base pairs in one copy of a haploid genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Genome size varies widely across species.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Invertebrates have small genomes, this is also correlated to a small number of transposable elements.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Fish and Amphibians have intermediate-size genomes, and birds have relatively small genomes but it has been suggested that birds lost a substantial portion of their genomes during the phase of transition to flight.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Before this loss, DNA methylation allows the adequate expansion of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] In humans, the nuclear genome comprises approximately 3.1 billion nucleotides of DNA, divided into 24 linear molecules, the shortest 45 000 000 nucleotides in length and the longest 248 000 000 nucleotides, each contained in a different chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] There is no clear and consistent correlation between morphological complexity and genome size in either prokaryotes or lower eukaryotes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Genome size is largely a function of the expansion and contraction of repetitive DNA elements.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Since genomes are very complex, one research strategy is to reduce the number of genes in a genome to the bare minimum and still have the organism in question survive.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] There is experimental work being done on minimal genomes for single cell organisms as well as minimal genomes for multi-cellular organisms (see developmental biology).
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The work is both *in vivo* and *in silico*.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] There are many enormous differences in size in genomes, specially mentioned before in the multicellular eukaryotic genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Much of this is due to the differing abundances of transposable elements, which evolve by creating new copies of themselves in the chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Eukaryote genomes often contain many thousands of copies of these elements, most of which have acquired mutations that make them defective.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] All the cells of an organism originate from a single cell, so they are expected to have identical genomes; however, in some cases, differences arise.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Both the process of copying DNA during cell division and exposure to environmental mutagens can result in mutations in somatic cells.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] In some cases, such mutations lead to cancer because they cause cells to divide more quickly and invade surrounding tissues.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] In certain lymphocytes in the human immune system, V(D)J recombination generates different genomic sequences such that each cell produces a unique antibody or T cell receptors.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] During meiosis, diploid cells divide twice to produce haploid germ cells.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] During this process, recombination results in a reshuffling of the genetic material from homologous chromosomes so each gamete has a unique genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Genome-wide reprogramming in mouse primordial germ cells involves epigenetic imprint erasure leading to totipotency.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Reprogramming is facilitated by active DNA demethylation, a process that entails the DNA base excision repair pathway.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] This pathway is employed in the erasure of CpG methylation (5mC) in primordial germ cells.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The erasure of 5mC occurs via its conversion to 5-hydroxymethylcytosine (5hmC) driven by high levels of the ten-eleven dioxygenase enzymes TET1 and TET2.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Genomes are more than the sum of an organism's genes and have traits that may be measured and studied without reference to the details of any particular genes and their products.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Duplications play a major role in shaping the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Duplication may range from extension of short tandem repeats, to duplication of a cluster of genes, and all the way to duplication of entire chromosomes or even entire genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Such duplications are probably fundamental to the creation of genetic novelty .
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Horizontal gene transfer is invoked to explain how there is often an extreme similarity between small portions of the genomes of two organisms that are otherwise very distantly related.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Horizontal gene transfer seems to be common among many microbes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Also, eukaryotic cells seem to have experienced a transfer of some genetic material from their chloroplast and mitochondrial genomes to their nuclear chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Recent empirical data suggest an important role of viruses and sub-viral RNA-networks to represent a main driving role to generate genetic novelty and natural genome editing.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Works of science fiction illustrate concerns about the availability of genome sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] Michael Crichton's 1990 novel *Jurassic Park* and the subsequent film tell the story of a billionaire who creates a theme park of cloned dinosaurs on a remote island, with disastrous outcomes.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] A geneticist extracts dinosaur DNA from the blood of ancient mosquitoes and fills in the gaps with DNA from modern species to create several species of dinosaurs.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] A chaos theorist is asked to give his expert opinion on the safety of engineering an ecosystem with the dinosaurs, and he repeatedly warns that the outcomes of the project will be unpredictable and ultimately uncontrollable.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] These warnings about the perils of using genomic information are a major theme of the book.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The 1997 film *Gattaca* is set in a futurist society where genomes of children are engineered to contain the most ideal combination of their parents' traits, and metrics such as risk of heart disease and predicted life expectancy are documented for each person based on their genome.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] People conceived outside of the eugenics program, known as "In-Valids" suffer discrimination and are relegated to menial occupations.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The protagonist of the film is an In-Valid who works to defy the supposed genetic odds and achieve his dream of working as a space navigator.
[src:genomics-biology/genome] The film warns against a future where genomic information fuels prejudice and extreme class differences between those who can and cannot afford genetically engineered children.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The **human genome** is a complete set of DNA sequences for each of the 22 autosomes and the two distinct sex chromosomes (X and Y).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] A small DNA molecule is found within individual mitochondria.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] These are usually treated separately as the nuclear genome and the mitochondrial genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Human genomes include both genes and various other types of functional DNA elements.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The latter is a diverse category that includes regulatory DNA scaffolding regions, telomeres, centromeres, and origins of replication.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In addition, there are large numbers of transposable elements, endogenized viral DNA, non-functional pseudogenes and simple, highly repetitive sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Introns make up a large percentage of the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Some of the genome is non-functional junk DNA, such as pseudogenes, but there is no firm consensus on the total amount of junk DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In 2000, scientists reported the sequencing of 88% of human genome, but as of 2020, at least 8% was still missing.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In 2021, scientists reported sequencing a complete, female genome (i.e., without the Y chromosome).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The human Y chromosome, consisting of 62,460,029 base pairs from a different cell line and found in all males, was sequenced completely in January 2022.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The current version of the standard reference genome is called GRCh38.p14 (July 2023).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] It consists of 22 autosomes plus one copy of the X chromosome and one copy of the Y chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] It contains approximately 3.1 billion base pairs.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] This represents the size of a composite genome based on data from multiple individuals but it is a good indication of the typical amount of DNA in a haploid set of chromosomes because the Y chromosome is quite small.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Most human cells are diploid so they contain twice as much DNA (~6.2 billion base pairs).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In 2023, a draft human pangenome reference was published.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] It is based on 47 genomes from people of varied ethnicity.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Plans are underway for an improved reference capturing still more biodiversity from a still wider sample.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The total length of the human reference genome does not represent the sequence of any specific individual, nor does it represent the sequence of all of the DNA found within a cell.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The human reference genome only includes one copy of each of the paired, homologous autosomes plus one copy of each of the two sex chromosomes (X and Y).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The total amount of DNA in this reference genome is 3.1 billion base pairs.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Protein-coding sequences are the most widely studied and best understood component of the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] These sequences ultimately lead to the production of all human proteins, although several biological processes (e.g.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] DNA rearrangements and alternative pre-mRNA splicing) can lead to the production of many more unique proteins than the number of protein-coding genes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The human reference genome contains somewhere between 19,000 and 20,000 protein-coding genes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] These genes contain an average of 10 introns and the average size of an intron is about 6 kb (6,000 bp).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] This means that the average size of a protein-coding gene is about 62 kb and these genes take up about 40% of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Exon sequences consist of coding DNA and untranslated regions (UTRs) at either end of the mature mRNA.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The total amount of coding DNA is about 1-2% of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Many people divide the genome into coding and non-coding DNA based on the idea that coding DNA is the most important functional component of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] About 98–99% of the human genome is non-coding DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Noncoding RNA molecules play many essential roles in cells, especially in the many reactions of protein synthesis and RNA processing.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Noncoding genes include those for tRNAs, ribosomal RNAs, microRNAs, snRNAs and long non-coding RNAs (lncRNAs).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The number of reported non-coding genes continues to rise slowly but the exact number in the human genome is yet to be determined.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Many RNAs are thought to be non-functional.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Many ncRNAs are critical elements in gene regulation and expression.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Noncoding RNA also contributes to epigenetics, transcription, RNA splicing, and the translational machinery.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The role of RNA in genetic regulation and disease offers a new potential level of unexplored genomic complexity.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Pseudogenes are inactive copies of protein-coding genes, often generated by gene duplication, that have become nonfunctional through the accumulation of inactivating mutations.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The number of pseudogenes in the human genome is on the order of 13,000, and in some chromosomes is nearly the same as the number of functional protein-coding genes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Gene duplication is a major mechanism through which new genetic material is generated during molecular evolution.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] For example, the olfactory receptor gene family is one of the best-documented examples of pseudogenes in the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] More than 60 percent of the genes in this family are non-functional pseudogenes in humans.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] By comparison, only 20 percent of genes in the mouse olfactory receptor gene family are pseudogenes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Research suggests that this is a species-specific characteristic, as the most closely related primates all have proportionally fewer pseudogenes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] This genetic discovery helps to explain the less acute sense of smell in humans relative to other mammals.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The human genome has many different regulatory sequences which are crucial to controlling gene expression.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Some scientists believe that these sequences make up 8% of the genome, but other scientists predict that 20% or more of the human genome might be devoted to regulatory sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] A value of 8% would correspond to approximately 10,000 bp of regulatory DNA per gene and a value of 20% corresponds to 25,000 bp of regulatory DNA per gene.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Many scientists think that these estimates are unreasonably high and conflict with the view that only 10% of the genome is functional and 90% is junk DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Regulatory sequences have been known since the late 1960s.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The first identification of regulatory sequences in the human genome relied on recombinant DNA technology.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Later with the advent of genomic sequencing, the identification of these sequences could be inferred by evolutionary conservation.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The evolutionary branch between the primates and mouse, for example, occurred 70–90 million years ago.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] So computer comparisons of gene sequences that identify conserved sequences will be an indication of their importance in functions such as gene regulation.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The results indicate that about 10% of the human genome is conserved.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Several hundred thousand human genome sequences have been sequenced and there is a considerable amount of variation between individuals.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Only 10% of the genome seems to be protected from mutations by purifying selection.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Repetitive DNA sequences comprise approximately 50% of the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] About 8% of the human genome consists of tandem DNA arrays or tandem repeats, low complexity repeat sequences that have multiple adjacent copies (e.g.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The tandem sequences may be of variable lengths, from two nucleotides to tens of nucleotides.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] These sequences are highly variable, even among closely related individuals, and so are used for genealogical DNA testing and forensic DNA analysis.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Repeated sequences of fewer than ten nucleotides (e.g. the dinucleotide repeat (AC)n) are termed microsatellite sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Among the microsatellite sequences, trinucleotide repeats are of particular importance, as sometimes occur within coding regions of genes for proteins and may lead to genetic disorders.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] For example, Huntington's disease results from an expansion of the trinucleotide repeat (CAG)n within the *Huntingtin* gene on human chromosome 4.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Telomeres (the ends of linear chromosomes) end with a microsatellite hexanucleotide repeat of the sequence (TTAGGG)n.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Tandem repeats of longer sequences (arrays of repeated sequences 10–60 nucleotides long) are termed minisatellites.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Transposable genetic elements, DNA sequences that can replicate and insert copies of themselves at other locations within a host genome, are an abundant component in the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The most abundant transposon lineage, *Alu*, has about 50,000 active copies, and can be inserted into intragenic and intergenic regions.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] One other lineage, LINE-1, has about 100 active copies per genome (the number varies between people).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Together with non-functional relics of old transposons, they account for over half of total human DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Sometimes called "jumping genes", transposons have played a major role in sculpting the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Some of these sequences represent endogenous retroviruses, DNA copies of viral sequences that have become permanently integrated into the genome and are now passed on to succeeding generations.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] There are also a significant number of retroviruses in human DNA, at least 3 of which have been proven to possess an important function (i.e., HIV-like functional HERV-K; envelope genes of non-functional viruses HERV-W and HERV-FRD play a role in placenta formation by inducing cell-cell fusion).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Mobile elements within the human genome can be classified into LTR retrotransposons (8.3% of total genome), SINEs (13.1% of total genome) including Alu elements, LINEs (20.4% of total genome), SVAs (SINE-VNTR-Alu) and Class II DNA transposons (2.9% of total genome).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] There is no consensus on what constitutes a "functional" element in the genome since geneticists, evolutionary biologists, and molecular biologists employ different definitions and methods.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Due to the ambiguity in the terminology, different schools of thought have emerged.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In evolutionary definitions, "functional" DNA, whether it is coding or non-coding, contributes to the fitness of the organism, and therefore is maintained by negative evolutionary pressure whereas "non-functional" DNA has no benefit to the organism and therefore is under neutral selective pressure.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] This type of DNA has been described as junk DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In genetic definitions, "functional" DNA is related to how DNA segments manifest by phenotype and "nonfunctional" is related to loss-of-function effects on the organism.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In biochemical definitions, "functional" DNA relates to DNA sequences that specify molecular products (e.g. noncoding RNAs) and biochemical activities with mechanistic roles in gene or genome regulation (i.e.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] DNA sequences that impact cellular level activity such as cell type, condition, and molecular processes).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] There is no consensus in the literature on the amount of functional DNA since, depending on how "function" is understood, ranges have been estimated from up to 90% of the human genome is likely nonfunctional DNA (junk DNA) to up to 80% of the genome is likely functional.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] It is also possible that junk DNA may acquire a function in the future and therefore may play a role in evolution, but this is likely to occur only very rarely.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Finally DNA that is deleterious to the organism and is under negative selective pressure is called garbage DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The first human genome sequences were published in nearly complete draft form in February 2001 by the Human Genome Project and Celera Corporation.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Completion of the Human Genome Project's sequencing effort was announced in 2004 with the publication of a draft genome sequence, leaving just 341 gaps in the sequence, representing highly repetitive and other DNA that could not be sequenced with the technology available at the time.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The human genome was the first of all vertebrates to be sequenced to such near-completion, and as of 2018, the diploid genomes of over a million individual humans had been determined using next-generation sequencing.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] These data are used worldwide in biomedical science, anthropology, forensics and other branches of science.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Such genomic studies have led to advances in the diagnosis and treatment of diseases, and to new insights in many fields of biology, including human evolution.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] By 2018, the total number of genes had been raised to at least 46,831, plus another 2300 micro-RNA genes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] A 2018 population survey found another 300 million bases of human genome that was not in the reference sequence.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Prior to the acquisition of the full genome sequence, estimates of the number of human genes ranged from 50,000 to 140,000 (with occasional vagueness about whether these estimates included non-protein coding genes).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] As genome sequence quality and the methods for identifying protein-coding genes improved, the count of recognized protein-coding genes dropped to 19,000–20,000.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In 2022, the Telomere-to-Telomere (T2T) consortium reported the complete sequence of a human female genome, filling all the gaps in the X chromosome (2020) and the 22 autosomes (May 2021).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The previously unsequenced parts contain immune response genes that help to adapt to and survive infections, as well as genes that are important for predicting drug response.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The completed human genome sequence will also provide better understanding of human formation as an individual organism and how humans vary both between each other and other species.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Although the 'completion' of the human genome project was announced in 2001, there remained hundreds of gaps, with about 5–10% of the total sequence remaining undetermined.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The missing genetic information was mostly in repetitive heterochromatic regions and near the centromeres and telomeres, but also some gene-encoding euchromatic regions.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] There remained 160 euchromatic gaps in 2015 when the sequences spanning another 50 formerly unsequenced regions were determined.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Only in 2020 was the first truly complete telomere-to-telomere sequence of a human chromosome determined, namely of the X chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The first complete telomere-to-telomere sequence of a human autosomal chromosome, chromosome 8, followed a year later.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The complete human genome (without Y chromosome) was published in 2021, while with Y chromosome in January 2022.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In 2023, the T2T consortium reported the complete sequence of a human Y chromosome, the last chromosome to be finished, correcting errors in the earlier reference and adding more than 30 million base pairs that were absent from GRCh38.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] A companion study that assembled 43 Y chromosomes from diverse lineages found that their length varies more than twofold between men.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In 2025, a research team preserved a digital copy of a human genome on a 5D memory crystal using femtosecond-laser inscription technology.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The genome was stored as part of a long-term archival effort intended to preserve biological information for extremely long time spans (billions of years) and is housed in the Memory of Mankind archive in a salt cave in Hallstatt, Austria.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] With the exception of identical twins, all humans show significant variation in genomic DNA sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The human reference genome (HRG) is used as a standard sequence reference.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The Genome Reference Consortium is responsible for updating the HRG.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Version 38 was released in December 2013.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Most studies of human genetic variation have focused on single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs), which are substitutions in individual bases along a chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Most analyses estimate that SNPs occur 1 in 1000 base pairs, on average, in the euchromatic human genome, although they do not occur at a uniform density.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Thus follows the popular statement that "we are all, regardless of race, genetically 99.9% the same", although this would be somewhat qualified by most geneticists.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] For example, a much larger fraction of the genome is now thought to be involved in copy number variation.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] A large-scale collaborative effort to catalog SNP variations in the human genome is being undertaken by the International HapMap Project.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The genomic loci and length of certain types of small repetitive sequences are highly variable from person to person, which is the basis of DNA fingerprinting and DNA paternity testing technologies.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The heterochromatic portions of the human genome, which total several hundred million base pairs, are also thought to be quite variable within the human population (they are so repetitive and so long that they cannot be accurately sequenced with current technology).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] These regions contain few genes, and it is unclear whether any significant phenotypic effect results from typical variation in repeats or heterochromatin.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Most gross genomic mutations in gamete germ cells probably result in inviable embryos; however, a number of human diseases are related to large-scale genomic abnormalities.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Down syndrome, Turner Syndrome, and a number of other diseases result from nondisjunction of entire chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Cancer cells frequently have aneuploidy of chromosomes and chromosome arms, although a cause and effect relationship between aneuploidy and cancer has not been established.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Whereas a genome sequence lists the order of every DNA base in a genome, a genome map identifies the landmarks.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] A genome map is less detailed than a genome sequence and aids in navigating around the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] An example of a variation map is the HapMap being developed by the International HapMap Project.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The HapMap is a haplotype map of the human genome, "which will describe the common patterns of human DNA sequence variation." It catalogs the patterns of small-scale variations in the genome that involve single DNA letters, or bases.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Researchers published the first sequence-based map of large-scale structural variation across the human genome in the journal *Nature* in May 2008.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Large-scale structural variations are differences in the genome among people that range from a few thousand to a few million DNA bases; some are gains or losses of stretches of genome sequence and others appear as re-arrangements of stretches of sequence.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] These variations include differences in the number of copies individuals have of a particular gene, deletions, translocations and inversions.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Structural variation refers to genetic variants that affect larger segments of the human genome, as opposed to point mutations.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Often, structural variants (SVs) are defined as variants of 50 base pairs (bp) or greater, such as deletions, duplications, insertions, inversions and other rearrangements.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] About 90% of structural variants are noncoding deletions but most individuals have more than a thousand such deletions; the size of deletions ranges from dozens of base pairs to tens of thousands of bp.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] On average, individuals carry ~3 rare structural variants that alter coding regions, e.g. delete exons.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] About 2% of individuals carry ultra-rare megabase-scale structural variants, especially rearrangements.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] That is, millions of base pairs may be inverted within a chromosome; ultra-rare means that they are only found in individuals or their family members and thus have arisen very recently.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) do not occur homogeneously across the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In fact, there is enormous diversity in SNP frequency between genes, reflecting different selective pressures on each gene as well as different mutation and recombination rates across the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] However, studies on SNPs are biased towards coding regions, the data generated from them are unlikely to reflect the overall distribution of SNPs throughout the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Therefore, the SNP Consortium protocol was designed to identify SNPs with no bias towards coding regions and the Consortium's 100,000 SNPs generally reflect sequence diversity across the human chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The SNP Consortium aims to expand the number of SNPs identified across the genome to 300 000 by the end of the first quarter of 2001.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Changes in **non-coding sequence** and synonymous changes in **coding sequence** are generally more common than non-synonymous changes, reflecting greater selective pressure reducing diversity at positions dictating amino acid identity.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Transitional changes are more common than transversions, with CpG dinucleotides showing the highest mutation rate, presumably due to deamination.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] A personal genome sequence is a (nearly) complete sequence of the chemical base pairs that make up the DNA of a single person.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Because medical treatments have different effects on different people due to genetic variations such as single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs), the analysis of personal genomes may lead to personalized medical treatment based on individual genotypes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The first personal genome sequence to be determined was that of Craig Venter in 2007.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Personal genomes had not been sequenced in the public Human Genome Project to protect the identity of volunteers who provided DNA samples.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] That sequence was derived from the DNA of several volunteers from a diverse population.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] However, early in the Venter-led Celera Genomics genome sequencing effort the decision was made to switch from sequencing a composite sample to using DNA from a single individual, later revealed to have been Venter himself.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Thus the Celera human genome sequence released in 2000 was largely that of one man.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Subsequent replacement of the early composite-derived data and determination of the diploid sequence, representing both sets of chromosomes, rather than a haploid sequence originally reported, allowed the release of the first personal genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In April 2008, that of James Watson was also completed.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In 2009, Stephen Quake published his own genome sequence derived from a sequencer of his own design, the Heliscope.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] A Stanford team led by Euan Ashley published a framework for the medical interpretation of human genomes implemented on Quake's genome and made whole genome-informed medical decisions for the first time.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] That team further extended the approach to the West family, the first family sequenced as part of Illumina's Personal Genome Sequencing program.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Since then hundreds of personal genome sequences have been released, including those of Desmond Tutu, and of a Paleo-Eskimo.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In 2012, the whole genome sequences of two family trios among 1092 genomes was made public.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In November 2013, a Spanish family made four personal exome datasets (about 1% of the genome) publicly available under a Creative Commons public domain license.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The Personal Genome Project (started in 2005) is among the few to make both genome sequences and corresponding medical phenotypes publicly available.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The sequencing of individual genomes further unveiled levels of genetic complexity that had not been appreciated before.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Personal genomics helped reveal the significant level of diversity in the human genome attributed not only to SNPs but structural variations as well.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] However, the application of such knowledge to the treatment of disease and in the medical field is only in its very beginnings.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Exome sequencing has become increasingly popular as a tool to aid in diagnosis of genetic disease because the exome contributes only 1% of the genomic sequence but accounts for roughly 85% of mutations that contribute significantly to disease.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In humans, gene knockouts naturally occur as heterozygous or homozygous loss-of-function gene knockouts.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] These knockouts are often difficult to distinguish, especially within heterogeneous genetic backgrounds.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] They are also difficult to find as they occur in low frequencies.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Populations with high rates of consanguinity, such as countries with high rates of first-cousin marriages, display the highest frequencies of homozygous gene knockouts.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Such populations include Pakistan, Iceland, and Amish populations.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] These populations with a high level of parental-relatedness have been subjects of human knock out research which has helped to determine the function of specific genes in humans.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] By distinguishing specific knockouts, researchers are able to use phenotypic analyses of these individuals to help characterize the gene that has been knocked out.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Knockouts in specific genes can cause genetic diseases, potentially have beneficial effects, or even result in no phenotypic effect at all.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] However, determining a knockout's phenotypic effect and in humans can be challenging.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Challenges to characterizing and clinically interpreting knockouts include difficulty calling of DNA variants, determining disruption of protein function (annotation), and considering the amount of influence mosaicism has on the phenotype.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] One major study that investigated human knockouts is the Pakistan Risk of Myocardial Infarction study.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] It was found that individuals possessing a heterozygous loss-of-function gene knockout for the APOC3 gene had lower triglycerides in the blood after consuming a high fat meal as compared to individuals without the mutation.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] However, individuals possessing homozygous loss-of-function gene knockouts of the APOC3 gene displayed the lowest level of triglycerides in the blood after the fat load test, as they produce no functional APOC3 protein.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In each cell of the human body, the human genome experiences, on average, tens of thousands of DNA damage events per day.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] These damage events can block genome replication or genome transcription, and if they are not repaired or are repaired incorrectly, they may lead to mutations, or other genome alterations in the human genome that threaten cell viability.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Most aspects of human biology involve both genetic (inherited) and non-genetic (environmental) factors.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Some inherited variation influences aspects of our biology that are not medical in nature (height, eye color, ability to taste or smell certain compounds, etc.).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Moreover, some genetic disorders only cause disease in combination with the appropriate environmental factors (such as diet).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] With these caveats, genetic disorders may be described as clinically defined diseases caused by genomic DNA sequence variation.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In the most straightforward cases, the disorder can be associated with variation in a single gene.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] For example, cystic fibrosis is caused by mutations in the CFTR gene and is the most common recessive disorder in caucasian populations with over 1,300 different mutations known.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Disease-causing mutations in specific genes are usually severe in terms of gene function and are rare, thus genetic disorders are similarly individually rare.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] However, since there are many genes that can vary to cause genetic disorders, in aggregate they constitute a significant component of known medical conditions, especially in pediatric medicine.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Molecularly characterized genetic disorders are those for which the underlying causal gene has been identified.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Currently there are approximately 2,200 such disorders annotated in the OMIM database.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Studies of genetic disorders are often performed by means of family-based studies.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In some instances, population based approaches are employed, particularly in the case of so-called founder populations such as those in Finland, French-Canada, Utah, Sardinia, etc.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Diagnosis and treatment of genetic disorders are usually performed by a geneticist-physician trained in clinical/medical genetics.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The results of the Human Genome Project are likely to provide increased availability of genetic testing for gene-related disorders, and eventually improved treatment.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Parents can be screened for hereditary conditions and counselled on the consequences, the probability of inheritance, and how to avoid or ameliorate it in their offspring.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] There are many different kinds of DNA sequence variation, ranging from complete extra or missing chromosomes down to single nucleotide changes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] It is generally presumed that much naturally occurring genetic variation in human populations is phenotypically neutral, i.e., has little or no detectable effect on the physiology of the individual (although there may be fractional differences in fitness defined over evolutionary time frames).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Genetic disorders can be caused by any or all known types of sequence variation.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] To molecularly characterize a new genetic disorder, it is necessary to establish a causal link between a particular genomic sequence variant and the clinical disease under investigation.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Such studies constitute the realm of human molecular genetics.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] With the advent of the Human Genome and International HapMap Project, it has become feasible to explore subtle genetic influences on many common disease conditions such as diabetes, asthma, migraine, schizophrenia, etc.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Thus there may be disagreement in particular cases whether a specific medical condition should be termed a genetic disorder.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Genome sequencing is now able to narrow the genome down to specific locations to more accurately find mutations that will result in a genetic disorder.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Copy number variants (CNVs) and single nucleotide variants (SNVs) are also able to be detected at the same time as genome sequencing with newer sequencing procedures available, called Next Generation Sequencing (NGS).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] This only analyzes a small portion of the genome, around 1–2%.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] NGS can also be used to identify carriers of diseases before conception.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The diseases that can be detected in this sequencing include Tay-Sachs disease, Bloom syndrome, Gaucher disease, Canavan disease, familial dysautonomia, cystic fibrosis, spinal muscular atrophy, and fragile-X syndrome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The Next Genome Sequencing can be narrowed down to specifically look for diseases more prevalent in certain ethnic populations.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Comparative genomics studies of mammalian genomes suggest that approximately 5% of the human genome has been conserved by evolution since the divergence of extant lineages approximately 200 million years ago, containing the vast majority of genes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The published chimpanzee genome differs from that of the human genome by 1.23% in direct sequence comparisons.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Around 20% of this figure is accounted for by variation within each species, leaving only ~1.06% consistent sequence divergence between humans and chimps at shared genes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] This nucleotide by nucleotide difference is dwarfed, however, by the portion of each genome that is not shared, including around 6% of functional genes that are unique to either humans or chimps.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In other words, the considerable observable differences between humans and chimps may be due as much or more to genome level variation in the number, function and expression of genes rather than DNA sequence changes in shared genes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Indeed, even within humans, there has been found to be a previously unappreciated amount of copy number variation (CNV) which can make up as much as 5–15% of the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In other words, between humans, there could be +/- 500,000,000 base pairs of DNA, some being active genes, others inactivated, or active at different levels.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The full significance of this finding remains to be seen.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] On average, a typical human protein-coding gene differs from its chimpanzee ortholog by only two amino acid substitutions; nearly one third of human genes have exactly the same protein translation as their chimpanzee orthologs.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] A major difference between the two genomes is human chromosome 2, which is equivalent to a fusion product of chimpanzee chromosomes 12 and 13.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] (later renamed to chromosomes 2A and 2B, respectively).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Humans have undergone an extraordinary loss of olfactory receptor genes during our recent evolution, which explains our relatively crude sense of smell compared to most other mammals.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Evolutionary evidence suggests that the emergence of color vision in humans and several other primate species has diminished the need for the sense of smell.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In September 2016, scientists reported that, based on human DNA genetic studies, all non-Africans in the world today can be traced to a single population that exited Africa between 50,000 and 80,000 years ago.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The human mitochondrial DNA is of tremendous interest to geneticists, since it undoubtedly plays a role in mitochondrial disease.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] It also sheds light on human evolution; for example, analysis of variation in the human mitochondrial genome has led to the postulation of a recent common ancestor for all humans on the maternal line of descent (see Mitochondrial Eve).
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Due to the damage induced by the exposure to Reactive Oxygen Species mitochondrial DNA (mtDNA) has a more rapid rate of variation than nuclear DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] This 20-fold higher mutation rate allows mtDNA to be used for more accurate tracing of maternal ancestry.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Studies of mtDNA in populations have allowed ancient migration paths to be traced, such as the migration of Native Americans from Siberia or Polynesians from southeastern Asia.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] It has also been used to show that there is no trace of Neanderthal DNA in the European gene mixture inherited through purely maternal lineage.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Due to the restrictive all or none manner of mtDNA inheritance, this result (no trace of Neanderthal mtDNA) would be likely unless there were a large percentage of Neanderthal ancestry, or there was strong positive selection for that mtDNA.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Epigenetics describes a variety of features of the human genome that transcend its primary DNA sequence, such as chromatin packaging, histone modifications and DNA methylation, and which are important in regulating gene expression, genome replication and other cellular processes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Epigenetic markers strengthen and weaken transcription of certain genes but do not affect the actual sequence of DNA nucleotides.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] DNA methylation is a major form of epigenetic control over gene expression and one of the most highly studied topics in epigenetics.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] During development, the human DNA methylation profile experiences dramatic changes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] In early germ line cells, the genome has very low methylation levels.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] These low levels generally describe active genes.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] As development progresses, parental imprinting tags lead to increased methylation activity.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Epigenetic patterns can be identified between tissues within an individual as well as between individuals themselves.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Identical genes that have differences only in their epigenetic state are called **epialleles**.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Epialleles can be placed into three categories: those directly determined by an individual's genotype, those influenced by genotype, and those entirely independent of genotype.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] The epigenome is also influenced significantly by environmental factors.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Diet, toxins, and hormones impact the epigenetic state.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Studies in dietary manipulation have demonstrated that methyl-deficient diets are associated with hypomethylation of the epigenome.
[src:genomics-biology/human-genome] Such studies establish epigenetics as an important interface between the environment and the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] In bacteria, the coding regions typically take up 88% of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The remaining 12% does not encode proteins, but much of it still has biological function through genes where the RNA transcript is functional (non-coding genes) and regulatory sequences, which means that almost all of the bacterial genome has a function.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The amount of coding DNA in eukaryotes is usually a much smaller fraction of the genome because eukaryotic genomes contain large amounts of repetitive DNA not found in prokaryotes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The human genome contains somewhere between 1–2% coding DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The exact number is not known because there are disputes over the number of functional coding exons and over the total size of the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] This means that 98–99% of the human genome consists of non-coding DNA and this includes many functional elements such as non-coding genes and regulatory sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Genome size in eukaryotes can vary over a wide range, even between closely related species.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] This puzzling observation was originally known as the C-value paradox where "C" refers to the haploid genome size.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The paradox was resolved with the discovery that most of the differences were due to the expansion and contraction of repetitive DNA and not the number of genes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Some researchers speculated that this repetitive DNA was mostly junk DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The reasons for the changes in genome size are still being worked out and this problem is called the C-value Enigma.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] This led to the observation that the number of genes does not seem to correlate with perceived notions of complexity because the number of genes seems to be relatively constant, an issue termed the G-value Paradox.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] For example, the genome of the unicellular *Polychaos dubium* (formerly known as *Amoeba dubia*) has been reported to contain more than 200 times the amount of DNA in humans (i.e. more than 600 billion pairs of bases vs a bit more than 3 billion in humans).
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The pufferfish *Takifugu rubripes* genome is only about one eighth the size of the human genome, yet seems to have a comparable number of genes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Genes take up about 30% of the pufferfish genome and the coding DNA is about 10%.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] (Non-coding DNA = 90%.) The reduced size of the pufferfish genome is due to a reduction in the length of introns and less repetitive DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The remainder of the genome (70% non-coding DNA) consists of promoters and regulatory sequences that are shorter than those in other plant species.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The genes contain introns but there are fewer of them and they are smaller than the introns in other plant genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] There are noncoding genes, including many copies of ribosomal RNA genes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The genome also contains telomere sequences and centromeres as expected.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Much of the repetitive DNA seen in other eukaryotes has been deleted from the bladderwort genome since that lineage split from those of other plants.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] About 59% of the bladderwort genome consists of transposon-related sequences but since the genome is so much smaller than other genomes, this represents a considerable reduction in the amount of this DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The authors of the original 2013 article note that claims of additional functional elements in the non-coding DNA of animals do not seem to apply to plant genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] There are two types of genes: protein coding genes and noncoding genes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Noncoding genes are an important part of non-coding DNA and they include genes for transfer RNA and ribosomal RNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] These genes were discovered in the 1960s.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Prokaryotic genomes contain genes for a number of other noncoding RNAs but noncoding RNA genes are much more common in eukaryotes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Typical classes of noncoding genes in eukaryotes include genes for small nuclear RNAs (snRNAs), small nucleolar RNAs (sno RNAs), microRNAs (miRNAs), short interfering RNAs (siRNAs), PIWI-interacting RNAs (piRNAs), and long noncoding RNAs (lncRNAs).
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] In addition, there are a number of unique RNA genes that produce catalytic RNAs.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Noncoding genes account for only a few percent of prokaryotic genomes but they can represent a vastly higher fraction in eukaryotic genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] In humans, the noncoding genes take up at least 6% of the genome, largely because there are hundreds of copies of ribosomal RNA genes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Protein-coding genes occupy about 38% of the genome; a fraction that is much higher than the coding region because genes contain large introns.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The total number of noncoding genes in the human genome is controversial.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Some scientists think that there are only about 5,000 noncoding genes while others believe that there may be more than 100,000 (see the article on Non-coding RNA).
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The difference is largely due to debate over the number of lncRNA genes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Promoters are DNA segments near the 5' end of the gene where transcription begins.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] They are the sites where RNA polymerase binds to initiate RNA synthesis.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Regulatory elements are sites that control the transcription of a nearby gene.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] They are almost always sequences where transcription factors bind to DNA and these transcription factors can either activate transcription (activators) or repress transcription (repressors).
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Regulatory elements were discovered in the 1960s and their general characteristics were worked out in the 1970s by studying specific transcription factors in bacteria and bacteriophage.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Promoters and regulatory sequences represent an abundant class of noncoding DNA but they mostly consist of a collection of relatively short sequences so they do not take up a very large fraction of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The exact amount of regulatory DNA in mammalian genome is unclear because it is difficult to distinguish between spurious transcription factor binding sites and those that are functional.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The binding characteristics of typical DNA-binding proteins were characterized in the 1970s and the biochemical properties of transcription factors predict that in cells with large genomes, the majority of binding sites will not be biologically functional.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Many regulatory sequences occur near promoters, usually upstream of the transcription start site of the gene.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Some occur within a gene and a few are located downstream of the transcription termination site.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] In eukaryotes, there are some regulatory sequences that are located at a considerable distance from the promoter region.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Some regulatory sequences are called enhancers or silencers but there is no rigorous definition that distinguishes them from other transcription factor binding sites.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Introns are the parts of a gene that are transcribed into the precursor RNA sequence, but ultimately removed by RNA splicing during the processing to mature RNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Introns are found in both types of genes: protein-coding genes and noncoding genes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] They are present in prokaryotes but they are much more common in eukaryotic genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Group I and group II introns take up only a small percentage of the genome when they are present.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Spliceosomal introns (see Figure) are only found in eukaryotes and they can represent a substantial proportion of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] In humans, for example, introns in protein-coding genes cover 37% of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Combining that with about 1% coding sequences means that protein-coding genes occupy about 38% of the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The calculations for noncoding genes are more complicated because there is considerable dispute over the total number of noncoding genes but taking only the well-defined examples means that noncoding genes occupy at least 6% of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The standard biochemistry and molecular biology textbooks describe non-coding nucleotides in mRNA located between the 5' end of the gene and the translation initiation codon.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] These regions are called 5'-untranslated regions or 5'-UTRs.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Similar regions called 3'-untranslated regions (3'-UTRs) are found at the end of the gene.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The 5'-UTRs and 3'UTRs are very short in bacteria but they can be several hundred nucleotides in length in eukaryotes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] They contain short elements that control the initiation of translation (5'-UTRs) and transcription termination (3'-UTRs) as well as regulatory elements that may control mRNA stability, processing, and targeting to different regions of the cell.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] DNA synthesis begins at specific sites called origins of replication.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] These are regions of the genome where the DNA replication machinery is assembled and the DNA is unwound to begin DNA synthesis.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] In most cases, replication proceeds in both directions from the replication origin.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The main features of replication origins are sequences where specific initiation proteins are bound.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] A typical replication origin covers about 100-200 base pairs of DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Prokaryotes have one origin of replication per chromosome or plasmid but there are usually multiple origins in eukaryotic chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The human genome contains about 100,000 origins of replication representing about 0.3% of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Centromeres are the sites where spindle fibers attach to newly replicated chromosomes in order to segregate them into daughter cells when the cell divides.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Each eukaryotic chromosome has a single functional centromere that is seen as a constricted region in a condensed metaphase chromosome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Centromeric DNA consists of a number of repetitive DNA sequences that often take up a significant fraction of the genome because each centromere can be millions of base pairs in length.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] In humans, for example, the sequences of all 24 centromeres have been determined and they account for about 6% of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] However, it is unlikely that all of this noncoding DNA is essential since there is considerable variation in the total amount of centromeric DNA in different individuals.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Centromeres are another example of functional noncoding DNA sequences that have been known for almost half a century and it is likely that they are more abundant than coding DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Telomeres are regions of repetitive DNA at the end of a chromosome, which provide protection from chromosomal deterioration during DNA replication.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Recent studies have shown that telomeres function to aid in its own stability.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Telomeric repeat-containing RNA (TERRA) are transcripts derived from telomeres.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] TERRA has been shown to maintain telomerase activity and lengthen the ends of chromosomes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Both prokaryotic and eukarotic genomes are organized into large loops of protein-bound DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] In eukaryotes, the bases of the loops are called scaffold attachment regions (SARs) and they consist of stretches of DNA that bind an RNA/protein complex to stabilize the loop.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] There are about 100,000 loops in the human genome and each SAR consists of about 100 bp of DNA, so the total amount of DNA devoted to SARs accounts for about 0.3% of the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Pseudogenes are mostly former genes that have become non-functional due to mutation, but the term also refers to inactive DNA sequences that are derived from RNAs produced by functional genes (processed pseudogenes).
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Pseudogenes are only a small fraction of noncoding DNA in prokaryotic genomes because they are eliminated by negative selection.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] In some eukaryotes, however, pseudogenes can accumulate because selection is not powerful enough to eliminate them (see Nearly neutral theory of molecular evolution).
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The human genome contains about 15,000 pseudogenes derived from protein-coding genes and an unknown number derived from noncoding genes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] They may cover a substantial fraction of the genome (~5%) since many of them contain former intron sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Pseudogenes are junk DNA by definition and they evolve at the neutral rate as expected for junk DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Some former pseudogenes have secondarily acquired a function and this leads some scientists to speculate that most pseudogenes are not junk because they have a yet-to-be-discovered function.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Transposons and retrotransposons are mobile genetic elements.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Retrotransposon repeated sequences, which include long interspersed nuclear elements (LINEs) and short interspersed nuclear elements (SINEs), account for a large proportion of the genomic sequences in many species.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Alu sequences, classified as a short interspersed nuclear element, are the most abundant mobile elements in the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Some examples have been found of SINEs exerting transcriptional control of some protein-encoding genes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Endogenous retrovirus sequences are the product of reverse transcription of retrovirus genomes into the genomes of germ cells.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Mutation within these retro-transcribed sequences can inactivate the viral genome.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Over 8% of the human genome is made up of (mostly decayed) endogenous retrovirus sequences, as part of the over 42% fraction that is recognizably derived of retrotransposons, while another 3% can be identified to be the remains of DNA transposons.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Much of the remaining half of the genome that is currently without an explained origin is expected to have found its origin in transposable elements that were active so long ago (> 200 million years) that random mutations have rendered them unrecognizable.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Genome size variation in at least two kinds of plants is mostly the result of retrotransposon sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Highly repetitive DNA consists of short stretches of DNA that are repeated many times in tandem (one after the other).
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The repeat segments are usually between 2 bp and 10 bp but longer ones are known.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Highly repetitive DNA is rare in prokaryotes but common in eukaryotes, especially those with large genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Most of the highly repetitive DNA is found in centromeres and telomeres (see above) and most of it is functional although some might be redundant.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The other significant fraction resides in short tandem repeats (STRs; also called microsatellites) consisting of short stretches of a simple repeat such as ATC.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] There are about 350,000 STRs in the human genome and they are scattered throughout the genome with an average length of about 25 repeats.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Variations in the number of STR repeats can cause genetic diseases when they lie within a gene but most of these regions appear to be non-functional junk DNA where the number of repeats can vary considerably from individual to individual.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] This is why these length differences are used extensively in DNA fingerprinting.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Junk DNA is DNA that has no biologically relevant function such as pseudogenes and fragments of once active transposons.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Bacteria and viral genomes have very little junk DNA but some eukaryotic genomes may have a substantial amount of junk DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The exact amount of nonfunctional DNA in humans and other species with large genomes has not been determined and there is considerable controversy in the scientific literature.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The nonfunctional DNA in bacterial genomes is mostly located in the intergenic fraction of non-coding DNA but in eukaryotic genomes it may also be found within introns.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] There are many examples of functional DNA elements in non-coding DNA, and it is erroneous to equate non-coding DNA with junk DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Genome-wide association studies (GWAS) identify linkages between alleles and observable traits such as phenotypes and diseases.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] Most of the associations are between single-nucleotide polymorphisms (SNPs) and the trait being examined and most of these SNPs are located in non-functional DNA.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] The association establishes a linkage that helps map the DNA region responsible for the trait but it does not necessarily identify the mutations causing the disease or phenotypic difference.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] SNPs that are tightly linked to traits are the ones most likely to identify a causal mutation.
[src:genomics-biology/non-coding-dna] (The association is referred to as tight linkage disequilibrium.) About 12% of these polymorphisms are found in coding regions; about 40% are located in introns; and most of the rest are found in intergenic regions, including regulatory sequences.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Microscopic means that it can be detected with optical microscopes, such as aneuploidies, marker chromosome, gross rearrangements and variation in chromosome size.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] The frequency in human population is thought to be underestimated due to the fact that some of these are not actually easy to identify.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] These structural abnormalities exist in 1 of every 375 live births by putative information.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Sub-microscopic structural variants are much harder to detect owing to their small size.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] The first study in 2004 that used DNA microarrays could detect tens of genetic loci that exhibited copy number variation, deletions and duplications, greater than 100 kilobases in the human genome.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] However, by 2015 whole genome sequencing studies could detect around 5,000 of structural variants as small as 100 base pairs encompassing approximately 20 megabases in each individual genome.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] These structural variants include deletions, tandem duplications, inversions, mobile element insertions.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] The mutation rate is also much higher than microscopic structural variants, estimated by two studies at 16% and 20% respectively, both of which are probably underestimates due to the challenges of accurately detecting structural variants.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] It has also been shown that the generation of spontaneous structural variants significantly increases the likelihood of generating further spontaneous single nucleotide variants or indels within 100 kilobases of the structural variation event.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Copy-number variation (CNV) is a large category of structural variation, which includes insertions, deletions and duplications.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] In recent studies, copy-number variations are tested on people who do not have genetic diseases, using methods that are used for quantitative SNP genotyping.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Results show that 28% of the suspected regions in the individuals actually do contain copy number variations.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Also, CNVs in human genome affect more nucleotides than Single Nucleotide Polymorphism (SNP).
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] It is also noteworthy that many of CNVs are not in coding regions.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Because CNVs are usually caused by unequal recombination, widespread similar sequences such as LINEs and SINEs may be a common mechanism of CNV creation.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] There are several inversions known which are related to human disease.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] For instance, recurrent 400kb inversion in factor VIII gene is a common cause of haemophilia A, and smaller inversions affecting idunorate 2-sulphatase (IDS) will cause Hunter syndrome.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] More examples include Angelman syndrome and Sotos syndrome.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] However, recent research shows that one person can have 56 putative inversions, thus the non-disease inversions are more common than previously supposed.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Also in this study it's indicated that inversion breakpoints are commonly associated with segmental duplications.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] One 900 kb inversion in the chromosome 17 is under positive selection and are predicted to increase its frequency in European population.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] More complex structural variants can occur include a combination of the above in a single event.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] The most common type of complex structural variation are non-tandem duplications, where sequence is duplicated and inserted in inverted or direct orientation into another part of the genome.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Other classes of complex structural variant include deletion-inversion-deletions, duplication-inversion-duplications, and tandem duplications with nested deletions.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] There are also cryptic translocations and segmental uniparental disomy (UPD).
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] There are increasing reports of these variations, but are more difficult to detect than traditional variations because these variants are balanced and array-based or PCR-based methods are not able to locate them.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Some genetic diseases are suspected to be caused by structural variations, but the relation is not very certain.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] It is not plausible to divide these variants into two classes as "normal" or "disease", because the actual output of the same variant will also vary.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Also, a few of the variants are actually positively selected for (mentioned above).
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] A series of studies have shown that gene disrupting spontaneous (*de novo*) CNVs disrupt genes approximately four times more frequently in autism than in controls and contribute to approximately 5–10% of cases.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Inherited variants also contribute to around 5–10% of cases of autism.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Structural variations also have its function in population genetics.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Different frequency of a same variation can be used as a genetic mark to infer relationship between populations in different areas.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] A complete comparison between human and chimpanzee structural variation also suggested that some of these may be fixed in one species because of its adaptative function.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] There are also deletions related to resistance against malaria and AIDS.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Also, some highly variable segments are thought to be caused by balancing selection, but there are also studies against this hypothesis.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Some of genome browsers and bioinformatic databases have a list of structural variations in human genome with an emphasis on CNVs, and can show them in the genome browsing page, for example, UCSC Genome Browser.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] Under the page viewing a part of the genome, there are "Common Cell CNVs" and "Structural Var" which can be enabled.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] On NCBI, there is a special page for structural variation.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] In that system, both "inner" and "outer" coordinates are shown; they are both not actual breakpoints, but surmised minimal and maximum range of sequence affected by the structural variation.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] The types are classified as insertion, loss, gain, inversion, LOH, everted, transchr and UPD.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] New methods have been developed to analyze human genetic structural variation at high resolutions.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] The methods used to test the genome are in either a specific targeted way or in a genome wide manner.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] For Genome wide tests, array-based comparative genome hybridization approaches bring the best genome wide scans to find new copy number variants.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] These techniques use DNA fragments that are labeled from a genome of interest and are hybridized, with another genome labeled differently, to arrays spotted with cloned DNA fragments.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] This reveals copy number differences between two genomes.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] For targeted genome examinations, the best assays for checking specific areas of the genome are primarily PCR based.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] The best established of the PCR based methods is real time quantitative polymerase chain reaction (qPCR).
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] A different approach is to specifically check certain areas that surround known segmental duplications since they are usually areas of copy number variation.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] An SNP genotyping method that offers independent fluorescence intensities for two alleles can be used to target the nucleotides in between two copies of a segmental duplication.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] From this, an increase in intensity from one of the alleles compared to the other can be observed.
[src:genomics-biology/structural-variation] With the development of next-generation sequencing (NGS) technology, four classes of strategies for the detection of structural variants with NGS data have been reported, with each being based on patterns that are diagnostic of different classes of SV.
